anllyfni]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1867]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1964]]\n[[Category:Former London and North Western Railway stations]]\n", "name_user": "Nempnet", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed Dunn citation anchor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penygroes_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Alfred Kubin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = #6495ED\n| name          = Alfred Kubin\n| image         = Nicola Perscheid - Alfred Kubin 1904b.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Alfred Leopold Isidor Kubin\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1877|04|10}}\n| birth_place   = [[Litom\u011b\u0159ice]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1959|08|20|1877|04|10}}\n| death_place   = [[Zwickledt]], [[Wernstein am Inn]]\n| nationality   = [[Austrians|Austrian]]\n| field         = Painting\n| training      = [[Academy of Fine Arts Munich|Munich Academy]]\n| movement      = [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolism]], [[Expressionism]]\n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by = [[Max Klinger]], [[Francisco Goya|Goya]]\n| influenced    = \n| awards        = \n}}\n\n'''Alfred Leopold Isidor Kubin''' (10 April 1877 \u2013 20 August 1959) was an Austrian [[printmaker]], illustrator, and occasional writer. Kubin is considered an important representative of [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolism]] and [[Expressionism]].\n\n== Biography ==\nKubin was born in [[Kingdom of Bohemia|Bohemia]] in the town of Leitmeritz, [[Austro-Hungarian Empire]] (now [[Litom\u011b\u0159ice]]). From 1892 to 1896, he was apprenticed to the [[Landscape photography|landscape photographer]] Alois Beer, although he learned little.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordartonline.com/groveart/view/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.001.0001/oao-9781884446054-e-7000048160|title=Kubin, Alfred|website=Grove Art Online|language=en|doi=10.1093/gao/9781884446054.001.0001/oao-9781884446054-e-7000048160|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> In 1896, he attempted suicide on his mother's grave, and his short stint in the Austrian army the following year ended with a nervous breakdown.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1898, Kubin began a period of artistic study at a private academy run by the painter Ludwig Schmitt-Reutte, before enrolling at the [[Academy of Fine Arts Munich|Munich Academy]] in 1899, without finishing his studies there. In Munich, Kubin discovered the works of [[Odilon Redon]], [[Edvard Munch]], [[James Ensor]], [[Henry de Groux]], and [[F\u00e9licien Rops]]. He was profoundly affected by the prints of [[Max Klinger]], and later recounted: \"Here a new art was thrown open to me, which offered free play for the imaginative expression of every conceivable world of feeling. Before putting the engravings away I swore that I would dedicate my life to the creation of similar works\".<ref name=\"ARN88\">Arnason & Wheeler 1986, p. 88.</ref> The [[aquatint]] technique used by Klinger and [[Francisco Goya|Goya]] influenced the style of his works of this period, which are mainly ink and [[wash (visual arts)|wash]] drawings of fantastical, often macabre subjects.<ref name=\":0\" /> Kubin produced a small number of oil paintings in the years between 1902 and 1910, but thereafter his output consisted of [[quill|pen and ink]] [[drawings]], [[watercolor]]s, and [[lithograph]]s. In 1911, he became associated with the ''[[Blaue Reiter]]'' group, and exhibited with them in the ''[[Der Sturm|Galerie Der Sturm]]'' in Berlin in 1913.<ref name=\"ARN88\" /> After that time, he lost contact with the artistic avant-garde.\n\nKubin is considered an important representative of [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolism]] and [[Expressionism]] and is noted for dark, spectral, symbolic fantasies, often assembled into thematic series of drawings. Like [[Oskar Kokoschka]] and [[Albert Paris G\u00fctersloh]], Kubin had both artistic and literary talent. He illustrated the works of [[Edgar Allan Poe]], [[E.T.A. Hoffmann]], and [[Fyodor Dostoevsky]], among others. Kubin also illustrated the German fantasy magazine ''[[Der Orchideengarten]]''.<ref name=\"studien\">Siegfried Sch\u00f6del, \n''Studien zu den phantastischen Erz\u00e4hlungen Gustav Meyrinks'', Universit\u00e4t Erlangen-N\u00fcrnberg, 1965, (p.27).</ref><ref name=\"nyt\">Rosenberg, Karen. 15 October 2008. [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/16/arts/design/16neue.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=%22alfred%20kubin%22%20+%20zwickeldt%22&st=cse Mapping the Shadowy Corners of the Subconscious]. The New York Times. Retrieved 3 April 2012.</ref>\n\nFrom 1906 until his death, he lived a withdrawn life in a small castle on a 12th-century estate in [[Zwickledt]], Upper Austria.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> In 1938, at the [[Anschluss]] of Austria and [[Nazi Germany]], his work was declared [[entartete Kunst]] or \"[[degenerate art]],\"<ref>Karl-Heinz Meissner, ''Alfred Kubin'', St\u00e4dtische Galerie im Lenbachhaus M\u00fcnchen, Edition Spangenberg, 1990 (p.114).</ref> but he managed to continue working during [[World War II]].\n\n== ''The Other Side'' ==\nKubin's only written work was ''Die andere Seite'' ({{Translation|''The Other Side''}}) (1908), a fantastic novel set in an oppressive imaginary land.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article110467833 |title=Artist creates a nightmare novel |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=24 October 1970 |access-date=30 March 2020 |page=13 |via=Trove }} </ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Robyn Walton | title=The Crime of Material Culture, the Condition of the Colonies and Utopian/Dystopian Impulses, 1908-10 | publication-date=2011 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/235140926 | accessdate=30 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Kubin, Alfred | author2=Lindley, Denver | author3=Kubin, Alfred, 1877-1959. Autobiography | title=The other side : a fantastic novel | publication-date=1969 | publisher=Gollancz | isbn=978-0-575-00345-3 }}</ref><ref>Kubin, Alfred, The Life and Art of Alfred Kubin, Dover 2017 (Bibliographic note). Viewable through Amazon.com's Look Inside feature for the book.</ref> The novel has an atmosphere of [[claustrophobia|claustrophobic]] [[absurdity]] similar to the writings of [[Franz Kafka]], who admired the book.<ref name=\"nyt\" /><ref>[[Franz Rottensteiner]],''The Fantasy Book: An Illustrated History from Dracula to Tolkien'' (p. 143) Collier Books, 1978. {{ISBN|0-02-053560-0}}</ref> The illustrations for the book were originally intended for ''[[The Golem (Meyrink novel)|The Golem]]'' by [[Gustav Meyrink]], but as that book was delayed Kubin instead worked his illustrations into his own novel.<ref name=\"studien\" />\n\n==Honours and awards==\n* City of Vienna Prize for Visual Arts (1950)\n* [[Grand Austrian State Prize for Visual Art]] (1951)\n* [[Austrian Medal for Science and Art]] (1957)\n* Gustav Klimt badge as an honorary member of the [[Vienna Secession]]\n\n== Collections ==\n\n* ''Kubin's Dance of Death and Other Drawings'' (1973) (art collection) ({{ISBN|9780486228846}})\n* ''The Life and Art of Alfred Kubin'' (2017) (autobiography) ({{ISBN|9780486815305}})\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Alfred Kubin - Dolmen, c. 1900-1902 - Google Art Project.jpg|''Dolmen'' ([[circa|c.]] 1900-1902)\nFile:Jede nacht besucht uns ein traum.jpg|''Jede nacht besucht uns ein traum'' (1900)\nFile:The past forgotten swallowed.jpg|''The Past Forgotten Swallowed'' (1901)\nFile:Angst by Alfred Kubin.jpg|''Angst'' (1903)\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Novels}}\n* [[List of Austrian artists and architects]]\n* [[List of Austrians]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* Arnason, H. H., & Wheeler, D. (1986). ''History of modern art: Painting, sculpture, architecture, photography''. Englewood Cliffs, N.J.: Prentice -Hall. {{ISBN|9780133903607}}\n* Assman, Peter ''Alfred Kubin 1877\u20131959'' Exhibition catalogue Brussels (Ixelles) 1997\n* ''Alfred Kubin'' Exhibition catalogue Neue Galerie New York 2008\n* Romana Schuler ''Alfred Kubin, Aus meinem Reich'' Exhibition catalogue Leopold Museum Vienna 2003\n* ''Traumgestalten. 100 Meisterwerke aus dem Besitz der Graphischen Sammlung Albertina'' Vienna 1990\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=Kubin,+Alfred | name=Alfred Kubin}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Alfred Kubin}}\n* [http://www.alfred-kubin.com www.alfred-kubin.com (in German)]\n* [http://www.aeiou.at/aeiou.encyclop.data.image.k/k895439a.jps ''Water Spirit'': oil painting by Alfred Kubin]\n* [http://alfred-kubin.blogspot.it More than 200 paintings and drawings by Alfred Kubin]\n* {{LCAuth|n80032690|Alfred Kubin|110|ue}}\n\n{{Der Blaue Reiter}}\n{{Degenerate art}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kubin, Alfred}}\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Austrian people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Austrian novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Austrian male writers]]\n[[Category:Academy of Fine Arts, Munich alumni]]\n[[Category:Austrian autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Austrian etchers]]\n[[Category:Austrian illustrators]]\n[[Category:Austrian fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:Austrian people of German Bohemian descent]]\n[[Category:Austrian speculative fiction artists]]\n[[Category:Male novelists]]\n[[Category:People from Litom\u011b\u0159ice]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Austrian Decoration for Science and Art]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Grand Austrian State Prize]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = #6495ED\n| name          = Alfred Kubin\n| image         = Nicola Perscheid - Alfred Kubin 1904b.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Alfred Leopold Isidor Kubin\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1877|04|10}}\n| birth_place   = [[Litom\u011b\u0159ice]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1959|08|20|1877|04|10}}\n| death_place   = [[Zwickledt]], [[Wernstein am Inn]]\n| nationality   = [[Austrians|Austrian]]\n| field         = Painting\n| training      = [[Academy of Fine Arts Munich|Munich Academy]]\n| movement      = [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolism]], [[Expressionism]]\n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by = [[Max Klinger]], [[Francisco Goya|Goya]]\n| influenced    = \n| awards        = \n}}\n\n'''Alfred Leopold Isidor Kubin''' (10 April 1877 \u2013 20 August 1959) was an Austrian [[printmaker]], illustrator, and occasional writer. Kubin is considered an important representative of [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolism]] and [[Expressionism]].\n\n== Biography ==\nKubin was born in [[Kingdom of Bohemia|Bohemia]] in the town of Leitmeritz, [[Austro-Hungarian Empire]] (now [[Litom\u011b\u0159ice]]). From 1892 to 1896, he was apprenticed to the [[Landscape photography|landscape photographer]] Alois Beer, although he learned little.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordartonline.com/groveart/view/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.001.0001/oao-9781884446054-e-7000048160|title=Kubin, Alfred|website=Grove Art Online|language=en|doi=10.1093/gao/9781884446054.001.0001/oao-9781884446054-e-7000048160|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> In 1896, he attempted suicide on his mother's grave, and his short stint in the Austrian army the following year ended with a nervous breakdown.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1898, Kubin began a period of artistic study at a private academy run by the painter Ludwig Schmitt-Reutte, before enrolling at the [[Academy of Fine Arts Munich|Munich Academy]] in 1899, without finishing his studies there. In Munich, Kubin discovered the works of [[Odilon Redon]], [[Edvard Munch]], [[James Ensor]], [[Henry de Groux]], and [[F\u00e9licien Rops]]. He was profoundly affected by the prints of [[Max Klinger]], and later recounted: \"Here a new art was thrown open to me, which offered free play for the imaginative expression of every conceivable world of feeling. Before putting the engravings away I swore that I would dedicate my life to the creation of similar works\".<ref name=\"ARN88\">Arnason & Wheeler 1986, p. 88.</ref> The [[aquatint]] technique used by Klinger and [[Francisco Goya|Goya]] influenced the style of his works of this period, which are mainly ink and [[wash (visual arts)|wash]] drawings of fantastical, often macabre subjects.<ref name=\":0\" /> Kubin produced a small number of oil paintings in the years between 1902 and 1910, but thereafter his output consisted of [[quill|pen and ink]] [[drawings]], [[watercolor]]s, and [[lithograph]]s. In 1911, he became associated with the ''[[Blaue Reiter]]'' group, and exhibited with them in the ''[[Der Sturm|Galerie Der Sturm]]'' in Berlin in 1913.<ref name=\"ARN88\" /> After that time, he lost contact with the artistic avant-garde.\n\nKubin is considered an important representative of [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolism]] and [[Expressionism]] and is noted for dark, spectral, symbolic fantasies, often assembled into thematic series of drawings. Like [[Oskar Kokoschka]] and [[Albert Paris G\u00fctersloh]], Kubin had both artistic and literary talent. He illustrated the works of [[Edgar Allan Poe]], [[E.T.A. Hoffmann]], and [[Fyodor Dostoevsky]], among others. Kubin also illustrated the German fantasy magazine ''[[Der Orchideengarten]]''.<ref name=\"studien\">Siegfried Sch\u00f6del, \n''Studien zu den phantastischen Erz\u00e4hlungen Gustav Meyrinks'', Universit\u00e4t Erlangen-N\u00fcrnberg, 1965, (p.27).</ref><ref name=\"nyt\">Rosenberg, Karen. 15 October 2008. [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/16/arts/design/16neue.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=%22alfred%20kubin%22%20+%20zwickeldt%22&st=cse Mapping the Shadowy Corners of the Subconscious]. The New York Times. Retrieved 3 April 2012.</ref>\n\nFrom 1906 until his death, he lived a withdrawn life in a small castle on a 12th-century estate in [[Zwickledt]], Upper Austria.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> In 1938, at the [[Anschluss]] of Austria and [[Nazi Germany]], his work was declared [[entartete Kunst]] or \"[[degenerate art]],\"<ref>Karl-Heinz Meissner, ''Alfred Kubin'', St\u00e4dtische Galerie im Lenbachhaus M\u00fcnchen, Edition Spangenberg, 1990 (p.114).</ref> but he managed to continue working during [[World War II]].\n\n== ''The Other Side'' ==\nKunbin's only written work was ''Die andere Seite'' ({{Translation|''The Other Side''}}) (1908), a fantastic novel set in an oppressive imaginary land.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article110467833 |title=Artist creates a nightmare novel |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=24 October 1970 |access-date=30 March 2020 |page=13 |via=Trove }} </ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Robyn Walton | title=The Crime of Material Culture, the Condition of the Colonies and Utopian/Dystopian Impulses, 1908-10 | publication-date=2011 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/235140926 | accessdate=30 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Kubin, Alfred | author2=Lindley, Denver | author3=Kubin, Alfred, 1877-1959. Autobiography | title=The other side : a fantastic novel | publication-date=1969 | publisher=Gollancz | isbn=978-0-575-00345-3 }}</ref><ref>Kubin, Alfred, The Life and Art of Alfred Kubin, Dover 2017 (Bibliographic note). Viewable through Amazon.com's Look Inside feature for the book.</ref> The novel has an atmosphere of [[claustrophobia|claustrophobic]] [[absurdity]] similar to the writings of [[Franz Kafka]], who admired the book.<ref name=\"nyt\" /><ref>[[Franz Rottensteiner]],''The Fantasy Book: An Illustrated History from Dracula to Tolkien'' (p. 143) Collier Books, 1978. {{ISBN|0-02-053560-0}}</ref> The illustrations for the book were originally intended for ''[[The Golem (Meyrink novel)|The Golem]]'' by [[Gustav Meyrink]], but as that book was delayed Kubin instead worked his illustrations into his own novel.<ref name=\"studien\" />\n\n==Honours and awards==\n* City of Vienna Prize for Visual Arts (1950)\n* [[Grand Austrian State Prize for Visual Art]] (1951)\n* [[Austrian Medal for Science and Art]] (1957)\n* Gustav Klimt badge as an honorary member of the [[Vienna Secession]]\n\n== Collections ==\n\n* ''Kubin's Dance of Death and Other Drawings'' (1973) (art collection) ({{ISBN|9780486228846}})\n* ''The Life and Art of Alfred Kubin'' (2017) (autobiography) ({{ISBN|9780486815305}})\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Alfred Kubin - Dolmen, c. 1900-1902 - Google Art Project.jpg|''Dolmen'' ([[circa|c.]] 1900-1902)\nFile:Jede nacht besucht uns ein traum.jpg|''Jede nacht besucht uns ein traum'' (1900)\nFile:The past forgotten swallowed.jpg|''The Past Forgotten Swallowed'' (1901)\nFile:Angst by Alfred Kubin.jpg|''Angst'' (1903)\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Novels}}\n* [[List of Austrian artists and architects]]\n* [[List of Austrians]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* Arnason, H. H., & Wheeler, D. (1986). ''History of modern art: Painting, sculpture, architecture, photography''. Englewood Cliffs, N.J.: Prentice -Hall. {{ISBN|9780133903607}}\n* Assman, Peter ''Alfred Kubin 1877\u20131959'' Exhibition catalogue Brussels (Ixelles) 1997\n* ''Alfred Kubin'' Exhibition catalogue Neue Galerie New York 2008\n* Romana Schuler ''Alfred Kubin, Aus meinem Reich'' Exhibition catalogue Leopold Museum Vienna 2003\n* ''Traumgestalten. 100 Meisterwerke aus dem Besitz der Graphischen Sammlung Albertina'' Vienna 1990\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=Kubin,+Alfred | name=Alfred Kubin}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Alfred Kubin}}\n* [http://www.alfred-kubin.com www.alfred-kubin.com (in German)]\n* [http://www.aeiou.at/aeiou.encyclop.data.image.k/k895439a.jps ''Water Spirit'': oil painting by Alfred Kubin]\n* [http://alfred-kubin.blogspot.it More than 200 paintings and drawings by Alfred Kubin]\n* {{LCAuth|n80032690|Alfred Kubin|110|ue}}\n\n{{Der Blaue Reiter}}\n{{Degenerate art}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kubin, Alfred}}\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Austrian people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Austrian novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Austrian male writers]]\n[[Category:Academy of Fine Arts, Munich alumni]]\n[[Category:Austrian autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Austrian etchers]]\n[[Category:Austrian illustrators]]\n[[Category:Austrian fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:Austrian people of German Bohemian descent]]\n[[Category:Austrian speculative fiction artists]]\n[[Category:Male novelists]]\n[[Category:People from Litom\u011b\u0159ice]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Austrian Decoration for Science and Art]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Grand Austrian State Prize]]\n", "name_user": "Powerdonne", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Kubin"}
{"title_page": "Adoor (State Assembly constituency)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Kerala Niyamasabha Constituency\n| constituency number    = 115\n| name                   = Adoor <br/> \u0d05\u0d1f\u0d42\u0d7c\n| existence              = 1965 - present\n| reserved               = [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|SC]]\n| current mla            = [[Chittayam Gopakumar]]\n| party                  = [[Communist Party of India]] \n| front                  = {{legend2|{{Left Democratic Front (Kerala)/meta/color}}|'''[[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|LDF]]'''|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n| electedbyyear          = [[2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly election|2016]]\n| district               = [[Pathanamthitta district|Pathanamthitta]]\n| electorate             =   2,08,432 (2016)\n| self governed segments =\n}}\n\n'''Adoor State assembly constituency''' ({{lang-ml|\u0d05\u0d1f\u0d42\u0d7c \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d2e\u0d38\u0d2d\u0d3e \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d4b\u0d1c\u0d15 \u0d2e\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d21\u0d32\u0d02}}) is one of the 140 [[Kerala Legislative Assembly|state legislative assembly]] constituencies at the state [[Kerala]] in southern [[India]]. It is also one of the 7 [[Kerala Legislative Assembly|state legislative assembly]] constituencies included in the [[Pathanamthitta (Lok Sabha constituency)|Pathanamthitta Lok Sabha constituency]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = https://pathanamthitta.nic.in/ml/elected-members-and-constituencies\n |website     = pathanamthitta.nic.in\n |title       = State Assembly Constituencies in Pathanamthitta district\n |accessdate  = 16 March 2020\n}}</ref> The current MLA is [[Chittayam Gopakumar]] of [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)|CPI(M)]]\n==See also==\n* [[Adoor]]\n* [[Pathanamthitta district]]\n* [[List of constituencies of the Kerala Legislative Assembly]]\n* [[2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly election]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kerala Assembly Constituencies}}\n\n{{Kerala Niyamasabha elections}}\n\n[[Category:State assembly constituencies in Pathanamthitta district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Kerala Niyamasabha Constituency\n| constituency number    = 115\n| name                   = Adoor <br/> \u0d05\u0d1f\u0d42\u0d7c\n| existence              = 1965 - present\n| reserved               = [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|SC]]\n| current mla            = [[Chittayam Gopakumar]]\n| party                  = [[Communist Party of India]] \n| front                  = {{legend2|{{Left Democratic Front (Kerala)/meta/color}}|'''[[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|LDF]]'''|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n| electedbyyear          = [[2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly election|2016]]\n| district               = [[Pathanamthitta district|Pathanamthitta]]\n| electorate             =   2,08,432 (2016)\n| self governed segments =\n}}\n\n'''Adoor State assembly constituency''' ({{lang-ml|\u0d05\u0d1f\u0d42\u0d7c \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d2e\u0d38\u0d2d\u0d3e \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d4b\u0d1c\u0d15 \u0d2e\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d21\u0d32\u0d02}}) is one of the 140 [[Kerala Legislative Assembly|state legislative assembly]] constituencies at the state [[Kerala]] in southern [[India]]. It is also one of the 7 [[Kerala Legislative Assembly|state legislative assembly]] constituencies included in the [[Pathanamthitta (Lok Sabha constituency)|Pathanamthitta Lok Sabha constituency]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = https://pathanamthitta.nic.in/ml/elected-members-and-constituencies\n |website     = pathanamthitta.nic.in\n |title       = State Assembly Constituencies in Pathanamthitta district\n |accessdate  = 16 March 2020\n}}</ref>\n==See also==\n* [[Adoor]]\n* [[Pathanamthitta district]]\n* [[List of constituencies of the Kerala Legislative Assembly]]\n* [[2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly election]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kerala Assembly Constituencies}}\n\n{{Kerala Niyamasabha elections}}\n\n[[Category:State assembly constituencies in Pathanamthitta district]]\n", "name_user": "Aswin8", "label": "safe", 